# Chapter Generation — Two-Pass

Chapter generation is **implemented as two passes** in `server/src/gemini.ts`, with
duration-aware budgets in `server/src/chapter-guidance.ts` and post-processing in
`server/src/validate-chapters.ts`.

## Current implementation

**Pass 1 — Boundary detection** (`detectBoundaries`)
- Sends transcript chunks to Gemini with a prompt focused only on finding topic-shift timestamps
- Output: `[{ startSeconds, topicSummary }]` (no polished titles yet)
- Goal: maximize recall of real section boundaries (intentionally over-detects)

**Pass 2 — Title + merge/split** (`titleAndRefine`)
- Sends Pass 1 boundaries plus the full chunked transcript back to Gemini
- Gemini writes concise chapter titles and merges over-granular splits / splits missed boundaries
- Output: final `[{ title, startSeconds }]`, then run through `validateChapters`

**Why two passes**
- Separates "where do topics change?" from "what should we call each section?"
- Fixes both over-segmentation (micro-chapter spam) and under-segmentation (single-topic
  videos collapsing to one chapter)
- Costs ~2× Gemini calls per video

## Refining further

If chapter quality still needs work, do NOT remove the two-pass structure. Prefer, in order:
1. Prompt tuning within Pass 1 / Pass 2 (recall in Pass 1, merge/split judgement in Pass 2)
2. Tuning `chapter-guidance.ts` budgets / `validate-chapters.ts` gap + cap logic
3. Embedding-based segmentation only as a last resort, and only if the user asks.
